<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Seventy men who looked into a box (1Sa 6:19).</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> - not a box...but the ark of the covenant.  BIG difference.  God had commanded &quot;Don't Touch!&quot;  to look inside they would have had to touch...specific command, specific punishment. (This also applies to the next point of the man who &quot;touched the box&quot; - #9 on your list)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Three thousand of the Levites' brothers, friends, and neighbors, who had become unruly (Exodus 32:27-28 ).</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  - not just unruly, but had begun to worship an idol they had formed instead of God!  Again, BIG difference.  God commanded their worship to Him only.<br>
<br>
As for the destruction of an entire population (no, I'm not going to address each of them separately)...same point.  God is loving and merciful, but He is also just.  These nations were as much a part of God's creation as Israel was, and God does not allow evil to continue unchecked.  God's command to destroy was designed to protect the Israelites from being ruined by the idolatry and immorality.  In most cases, against the Canaanites, they were up to their ears in intense idolatry, and consistent rebellion against God.  This was not the right kind of living that God had commanded and needed to be removed.  If it continued, it would affect all of Israel (as it later did in the book of Judges)  God's purpose was to keep the people's faith and religion uncontaminated.  One group God commanded destroyed were a group of terrorists...they lived to attack others and carry off their wealth.  This group consistently attacked the Israelites, and the Israelites would never live peacefully in the promised land as long as this group existed.<br>
<br>
