Also, what sort of dicipline(if any) would you have inflicted on the Isrealites? God has some pretty explicit laws that they broke, should he have just said, &quot;Oh well, those weren't important.&quot; And let things go or what? Remember, this is all based on the belief that there is a God that created us and all that we know.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->What kind of god would I worship?  Well there are a couple terms in there that need some tighter agreement of definition before I can really answer that.  First of all, what is worship?  If by worship you mean service to god, then I would only worship a god who required of me the service of being the best person I can by every measure I have available to me, chief among those love, reason, logic and skepticism.  I could not worship any deity who was jealous, selfish, insecure and hate-filled.  If by worship you mean tithe or sacrifice, then I don’t see that as appropriate ‘worship’ for any type of Supreme Being.  That would be like me taxing my kids’ allowances and in reality, only serves the church as a capitalistic predator, not god himself.  Second is what is a god?  I see the xian god as small and petty.  A god for me would be a supreme power, a creator, a first mover who moved not because he wanted me to scrape and kneel, but because the creation was worth creating.  My idea of god would not require my worship, or even acknowledgement.  So I guess the short answer for you about what kind of god would I worship is, “I wouldn’t.”  <br>
<br>
Next I will address the Israelites and god’s discipline.  What sort of discipline would I expect of god?  I would expect exactly what he did, which is nothing.  The story does a nice little deal on attributing the atrocities to god, but as we have seen from the number of plagues god visited upon us this year and the number of burning bushes telling us where to stand or find milk and honey, god is not active in the real world.  Now if the story were to be believed and he killed wantonly, gave the possessions of others unjustly, and tortured arbitrarily (which is what ‘punishment’ is when it meted out to the innocent) then I would say you follow the devil himself, not god.  It is a total self-delusion to blindly accept those laws that suit you and disregard those that you apathetically decide to ignore.  God has lots of pretty explicit laws.  Take for example, “Thou shalt not kill.”  Straightforward and clear, yet someone has to kill all these rule-breakers god says must die.  Who is to kill the stick gatherer, drunkard or idolater?  The disrespectful child, unwed mother or homosexual?  Why can’t god kill them if he is so damn powerful, he was able to smite those who presumed to touch his magic luggage, didn’t he?  Do you have to keep a pagan on retainer to do all your executions?  His minions are forbidden killing, then required to.  If it is so convenient to say, “Oh, well that shellfish junk and the whole wool/cotton thing aren’t important.” then why not any of the others as well?  Why not the ones where 130,000 people have to die without choice or defense, wouldn’t that be preferable to ignore than the ones like shellfish where it is a personal decision and you fall on your own choice?  So I guess the short answer for you about what kind of punishment I would inflict on Israel is, “I wouldn’t.”<br>
<br>
The kind of god I would worship is one who would not require me to and only asked that I be the best I can.  So I guess I am worshiping him every day already, he doesn’t care, neither do I and we both are happy that way.<br>
<br>
Now, in reply to the misconstruing of my acceptance for the sake of argument that god exists in contrast to my belief that here and now are all we know we get, I will again (surprise) have to disagree.  Even among different xian cults there is a disagreement about heaven, hell, oblivion, who gets raised, who is saved, who gets recycled, where, when and how you are shuffled off this mortal coil and to what result.  I conceded that god existed for this argument, I did not concede that the bible was inerrant, there existed a heaven or hell or any of the other tag-ons you all seem so excited to just toss into the soup.  You all agree there is this god guy, and that the bible is his word.  I am accepting the first and calling into question his ethics based on the second.  Period.  That’s all.  Everything else is your luggage and I never agreed to carry it.  <br>
<br>
We can all agree that here and now is something we get.  We may disagree that it is ALL we get, but we at least agree that we get this much anyway.  (I refuse to engage any Nihilists here.)  We seem to have a quorum on that there are some requirements that must be met to get into heaven, irrespective of what they are, we can concede that there are some.  Consequently, anyone, even god, who takes someone’s life before they met that qualification, has unjustly denied them their chance at heaven.  Now god may be omniscient, in which case you argue that he knew they’d never make the cut, to which I respond that your argument totally invalidates the concept of choice and freewill, and therefore your explanation of god.<br>
